item.description: "Anything that just costs money is cheap." -- John Steinbeck

item.title: Kendall add a quote by J.D. Salinger
item.description: "I'm a kind of paranoiac in reverse. I suspect people of plotting to make me happy." -- J.D. Salinger

item.title: Kendall add a quote by Fyodor Dostoevsky
item.description: "What is hell? I maintain that it is the suffering of being unable to love." -- Fyodor Dostoevsky

item.title: Kendall add a quote by William Shakespeare
item.description: "The fool doth think he is wise, but the wise man knows himself to be a fool." -- William Shakespeare

item.title: Kendall add a quote by J.D. Salinger
item.description: "The fact is always obvious much too late, but the most singular difference between happiness and joy is that happiness is a solid and joy a liquid." -- J.D. Salinger

item.title: Kendall add a quote by Flannery O'Connor
item.description: "I don't deserve any credit for turning the other cheek as my tongue is always in it." -- Flannery O'Connor

item.title: Kendall add a quote by Oscar Wilde
item.description: "I am so clever that sometimes I don't understand a single word of what I am saying." -- Oscar Wilde

item.title: Kendall add a quote by J.D. Salinger
item.description: "You're lucky if you get time to sneeze in this goddam phenomenal world." -- J.D. Salinger

item.title: Kendall add a quote by Flannery O'Connor
item.description: "The truth does not change according to our ability to stomach it." -- Flannery O'Connor

item.title: Kendall add a quote by Chuck Klosterman
item.description: "Important things are inevitably cliche, but nobody wants to admit that." -- Chuck Klosterman

item.title: Kendall add a quote by William Faulkner
item.description: "Given the choice between the experience of pain and nothing, I would choose pain." -- William Faulkner

item.title: Kendall add a quote by John Steinbeck
item.description: "We have only one story. All novels, all poetry, are built on the neverending contest in ourselves of good and evil. And it occurs to me that evil must constantly respawn, while good, while virtue, is immortal. Vice has always a new fresh young face, while virtue is venerable as nothing else in the world is." -- John Steinbeck
